      {
        "id": "R193JQEY0K71F6",
        "title": "Proven ineffective \u2014 does NOT remove chlorine (verified against RO system) \u2014 do NOT use for babies",
        "body": "Proven ineffective \u2014 does NOT remove chlorine (verified against RO system) \u2014 do NOT use for babiesI am writing this because people, especially parents, deserve accurate information.This product claims to remove \u201charsh chemicals\u201d like chlorine. I tested that claim directly using multi-parameter water test strips.I tested:\u2022 Unfiltered tap water\u2022 Filtered water at normal flow\u2022 Filtered water after proper activation (2\u20133 minutes hot water as instructed)\u2022 Filtered water at very slow flow to increase contact timeMost importantly, I also tested water from a reverse osmosis (RO) system as a control. The RO water showed zero chlorine, confirming that the test strips and method are working correctly.Across every test condition, the results were the same:\u2022 Tap water chlorine: approximately 0.5\u20131 ppm\u2022 Filtered water chlorine: approximately 0.5\u20131 ppmThere was no meaningful reduction in chlorine.At the same time, total dissolved solids (PPM) increased after filtration, meaning the water contained more dissolved material after passing through the unit.Based on direct testing, this product does not remove chlorine and does not meaningfully improve the water quality in that regard. The comparison with the RO system makes this clear, as the RO water showed zero chlorine while this product showed no change.Final verdict:\u2022 Does not perform as advertised\u2022 Does not remove chlorine\u2022 Increases dissolved solids\u2022 Fails under controlled testingIf you are buying this to make bath water safer for your baby, do not rely on this product. It does not do what it claims.",
        "rating": 1,
        "date": {
          "raw": "Reviewed in the United States on March 29, 2026"
        },
